 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# The Biggest Lie in Reloading Testing\n",
    "\n",
    "You've probably heard claims like: 'This load gives me 5 fps SD over 10 shots!' or 'Look at this 0.3\" group!'\n",
    "\n",
    "But how reliable are these small-sample results? Let's simulate and see."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import seaborn as sns\n",
    "import ipywidgets as widgets\n",
    "from IPython.display import display\n",
    "from scipy import stats\n",
    "\n",
    "# Set seaborn style for better colors\n",
    "sns.set_style('whitegrid')\n",
    "sns.set_palette('viridis')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Simulation parameters\n",
    "true_mean_velocity = 2500  # fps\n",
    "true_sd_velocity = 12     # fps\n",
    "n_total_shots = 1000\n",
    "\n",
    "# Generate the 'true' population of velocities\n",
    "np.random.seed(42)  # for reproducibility\n",
    "velocities = np.random.normal(true_mean_velocity, true_sd_velocity, n_total_shots)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Velocity Consistency: Small Samples Can Lie\n",
    "\n",
    "Imagine you have a load with a true velocity standard deviation of 12 fps. You shoot a small sample and get a low SD. How often is that just luck?\n",
    "\n",
    "Use the slider below to change the sample size and see the distribution of sample standard deviations."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def get_sample_sds(sample_size, n_simulations=1000):\n",
    "    sds = []\n",
    "    for _ in range(n_simulations):\n",
    "        sample = np.random.choice(velocities, sample_size, replace=False)\n",
    "        sds.append(np.std(sample, ddof=1))  # sample standard deviation\n",
    "    return sds\n",
    "\n",
    "def plot_velocity_sds(sample_size):\n",
    "    sds = get_sample_sds(sample_size)\n",
    "    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))\n",
    "    ax = sns.histplot(sds, bins=50, kde=True, color='skyblue', edgecolor='navy', alpha=0.7)\n",
    "    ax.axvline(true_sd_velocity, color='red', linestyle='--', linewidth=3, label=f'True SD: {true_sd_velocity} fps')\n",
    "    ax.axvline(np.mean(sds), color='green', linestyle='-', linewidth=2, label=f'Mean Sample SD: {np.mean(sds):.1f} fps')\n",
    "    plt.xlabel('Sample Standard Deviation (fps)', fontsize=14)\n",
    "    plt.ylabel('Frequency', fontsize=14)\n",
    "    plt.title(f'Distribution of Sample SDs for {sample_size}-Shot Samples\\n(True SD = {true_sd_velocity} fps)', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')\n",
    "    plt.legend(fontsize=12)\n",
    "    plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Interactive slider\n",
    "sample_slider = widgets.IntSlider(value=10, min=5, max=50, step=5, description='Sample Size:', style={'description_width': 'initial'})\n",
    "widgets.interact(plot_velocity_sds, sample_size=sample_slider)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Key Takeaway:** A low SD over 10 shots proves almost nothing. It happens by luck more often than you think. Notice how even with 20 shots, the distribution is still wide!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Group Sizes: Even Worse for Accuracy\n",
    "\n",
    "Accuracy groups are even more misleading with small samples. A mediocre rifle can produce 'amazing' looking 5-shot groups just by chance.\n",
    "\n",
    "Below, we simulate a rifle with 1\" dispersion at 100 yards. Each group is 5 shots. Click 'New Groups' to see how random luck can make groups look tight."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Simulation for accuracy groups\n",
    "true_group_dispersion = 1.0  # inch at 100 yards\n",
    "\n",
    "def generate_group(size=5):\n",
    "    x = np.random.normal(0, true_group_dispersion, size)\n",
    "    y = np.random.normal(0, true_group_dispersion, size)\n",
    "    return x, y\n",
    "\n",
    "def plot_accuracy_groups():\n",
    "    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(18, 6))\n",
    "    group_sizes = []\n",
    "    for i, ax in enumerate(axes):\n",
    "        x, y = generate_group()\n",
    "        # Calculate group size as max distance from center\n",
    "        distances = np.sqrt(x**2 + y**2)\n",
    "        group_size = np.max(distances) * 2  # diameter\n",
    "        group_sizes.append(group_size)\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Color code based on tightness\n",
    "        color = 'red' if group_size < 1 else 'orange' if group_size < 2 else 'green'\n",
    "        ax.scatter(x, y, color=color, s=100, alpha=0.8, edgecolors='black')\n",
    "        ax.scatter(0, 0, color='black', marker='+', s=200, linewidth=3, label='Point of Aim')\n",
    "        ax.set_xlim(-3, 3)\n",
    "        ax.set_ylim(-3, 3)\n",
    "        ax.set_aspect('equal')\n",
    "        ax.set_title(f'Group {i+1}: {group_size:.2f}\" diameter', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')\n",
    "        ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "        ax.legend()\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Overall title\n",
    "    fig.suptitle(f'Simulated 5-Shot Groups (True dispersion = {true_group_dispersion}\" SD)', fontsize=16)\n",
    "    plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "    \n",
    "    print(f\"Group sizes: {', '.join([f'{s:.2f}\"' for s in group_sizes])}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Interactive button\n",
    "new_groups_button = widgets.Button(description='New Groups', button_style='primary')\n",
    "new_groups_button.on_click(lambda b: plot_accuracy_groups())\n",
    "display(new_groups_button)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Initial plot\n",
    "plot_accuracy_groups()"
   ]
  },
   {
    "cell_type": "markdown",
    "metadata": {},
    "source": [
      "**Observation:** Even with a mediocre rifle, you can get groups that look sub-MOA just by random chance. Always shoot more rounds for a true picture!"
    },
    {
     "cell_type": "markdown",
     "metadata": {},
     "source": [
      "## The Real Key to Precision: Component Consistency\n",
      "\n",
      "If small tests can fool you, what really makes a load accurate? The truth is simple: most of the precision and accuracy comes from consistency. A big part of your results depends on the quality and steadiness of your ammo parts.\n",
      "\n",
      "Think of it like this: Imagine you're baking cookies. If your ingredients are all the same quality and measured exactly each time, your cookies turn out pretty much the same. But if the flour is lumpy or the sugar is clumpy, no matter how careful you are with the recipe, the cookies won't be consistent.\n",
      "\n",
      "In reloading, it's similar. For example, if your bullets are unbalanced or not perfectly round (called non-concentric), they will wobble in flight. This wobble is called yaw, and it's something you can't fix as a handloader. The bullet might start straight, but that imbalance makes it twist and turn, ruining your accuracy. It's like throwing a crooked dart – no matter how good your aim, it won't hit the bullseye.\n",
      "\n",
      "### Statistical Analysis of Reloading Components\n",
      "\n",
      "To truly understand component consistency, ask yourself: What am I measuring and how does it fundamentally affect the end result?\n",
      "\n",
      "For instance, when measuring case volume, you're assessing the internal capacity that determines powder charge and thus pressure and velocity. However, with premium brands like Lapua or Alpha, there's often no correlation between brass weight and case volume—lighter cases might hold just as much powder as heavier ones, making weight alone a poor predictor of performance.\n",
      "\n",
      "Remember situational dependence: techniques like uniforming primer pockets can seem like a good idea for consistency, but if not executed perfectly, they might introduce new inconsistencies or even worsen results. It's not always beneficial—context matters.\n",
      "\n",
      "Examples of key measurements:\n",
      "- **Bullet runout**: Measures how off-center the bullet is seated. Even 0.001\" of runout can cause yaw, leading to groups opening up by 0.5\" or more at 100 yards.\n",
      "- **Powder charge variation**: A 0.1 grain inconsistency can result in 20-30 fps velocity spread, directly impacting precision through pressure variations.\n",
      "- **Case neck tension**: Too loose, and bullets shift; too tight, and pressures rise unevenly. Statistical analysis shows optimal tension reduces group sizes by 20-40%.\n",
      "\n",
      "So, focus on using high-quality, consistent components. Check your bullets for balance, use good powder that meters evenly, and make sure your cases are uniform. That consistency will give you real precision, not just lucky small-sample results."
     ]
    },
     {
